{
  "$schema": "../../schema/pathway.schema.json",
  "id": "cholesterol-biosynthesis",
  "name": "Cholesterol biosynthesis (mevalonate pathway)",
  "category": "lipid-metabolism",
  "summary": "The ~30-carbon route from acetyl-CoA through mevalonate and squalene to cholesterol, with HMG-CoA reductase as the committed, rate-limiting, statin-targeted step.",
  "description": "Cholesterol biosynthesis converts cytosolic acetyl-CoA into the C27 sterol cholesterol in roughly thirty enzymatic steps organised into four stages. **(1) Mevalonate stage:** two acetyl-CoA condense to acetoacetyl-CoA, a third acetyl-CoA is added to form HMG-CoA, and HMG-CoA is reduced by NADPH to mevalonate. This reduction, catalysed by ER-anchored HMG-CoA reductase (HMGCR), is the committed and rate-limiting step of the whole pathway and the pharmacological target of the statins. **(2) Isoprenoid-activation stage:** three ATP-dependent steps phosphorylate and decarboxylate mevalonate to the C5 building block isopentenyl diphosphate (IPP), which isomerises to dimethylallyl diphosphate (DMAPP). **(3) Condensation stage:** head-to-tail prenyl condensations build geranyl-PP (C10) and farnesyl-PP (C15); two farnesyl-PP are then reductively fused by squalene synthase to the C30 hydrocarbon squalene. Squalene monooxygenase (SQLE) epoxidises squalene — the second rate-limiting/flux-controlling step — and lanosterol synthase cyclises 2,3-oxidosqualene into the first sterol, lanosterol. **(4) Lanosterol-to-cholesterol stage:** ~19 reactions remove three methyl groups (one at C14 by CYP51A1, two at C4 by the MSMO1/NSDHL/HSD17B7 cycle), shift and reduce ring/side-chain double bonds (TM7SF2, EBP, SC5D, DHCR7, DHCR24) to yield cholesterol. Two interconvertible sub-routes exist: the **Kandutsch–Russell** pathway (DHCR24 reduces the Δ24 bond early, giving zymosterol → lathosterol → 7-dehydrocholesterol → cholesterol; this KEGG M00101 backbone is modelled here) and the **Bloch** pathway (the Δ24 bond is retained until the terminal desmosterol → cholesterol reduction). Output is controlled by the SREBP-2 transcription factor (induces the pathway genes when ER sterols fall), by sterol-accelerated INSIG-dependent degradation and AMPK phosphorylation of HMGCR, and by competitive statin inhibition. Cholesterol is the precursor of steroid hormones, bile acids and vitamin D, and a key membrane component.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["liver", "intestine", "adrenal-cortex", "skin", "ubiquitous"],
